Remarks: [sono]

Two perched cuckoos sitting on branches a couple metres apart, facing each other. One cuckoo giving a softer call, being answered by harsher, nasally "raah" of the other bird. Louder call is from bird facing microphone. Calls given with simultaneously tail raising. Both birds appeared to be adult, possibly courtship behaviour?  Recorded around dusk with Sennheiser ME66/K6 with Sony PCM-M10. No filtering or editing other than removing very brief (<1 s) section between first and second calls when microphone got bumped.

This is the first time I've ever heard this species anywhere, let alone in Amazonia, where it's a very low-density winterer that I see probably once every 2 or 3 years in situations much like this one, but previously always silent.  As the mixed species canopy flock approached the tower, I heard this unfamiliar vireo-like song that I recorded and then played back.  I detected no clear response to playback and the vocalizing had stopped even before I began to play.  However, several minutes later a V. altiloquus appeared in the crown of a 30+m emergent tree (Goupia glabra) next to the tower and persisted there long enough for me to collect it.  The specimen is deposited at the INPA collection here in Manaus.  I cannot be sure the individual I collected was the same bird that sang, and I base the ID of this cut on its similarity to the others here on XC.  However, I'm guessing it is all the same bird.  The habitat, then, is canopy of primary terra firme forest.  The original recording is in wav format and is only slightly longer, with more background species at the end that were trimmed off in this cut.  It began softly and grows louder when I increased the recording level; however, in this cut i boosted the level at the start to keep it roughly even throughout.

Location: Elon University (near  Elon), Alamance County, North Carolina
Type: adult, imitates Cope's gray treefrog at 48s, male, mimicry/imitation, song
Remarks:
Recording made in the field on the campus of Elon University using a Zoom H4 solid state audio recorder attached to a Sennheiser ME62 omnidirectional microphone mounted in a 60-cm Telinga pro-universal parabola. I observed the focal bird ("Hardy") for 2hrs continuously starting at civil twilight. Hardy sang spontaneously for 62min of the 120min recording period, and I'm uploading a representative 1min subset of his singing behavior. The only modification made to the recording was to maximize the amplitude. At 0:48 Hardy imitates Cope's gray treefrog, a locally common frog species. For more information, contact me.

The Northern Mockingbird was imitating variety of calls. The imitations of the birds I identify are Blue Jay, Tufted Tit Mouse, Hairy Woodpecker, American Robin, House Sparrow, Tree Swallow, Rough-winged Swallow, Red-bellied Woodpecker, Grey Catbird, Song Sparrow, Wood Thrush, American Goldfinch (but there are natural calls also of Goldfinches) American Kestrel, Northern Cardinal, Baltimore Oriole, Purple Martin, Killdeer, Eastern Phoebe, Merlin and many others sounded familiar but I could not identify as the source of the sound was very different.  Many of the songs were variation of the same species. For example, there are four different types of calls of Tree Swallows. Amazing mimicry, I believe there some birds which I think are tropical birds, because they sound familiar.

Remarks:
Recorded with a Wildtronics parabolic dish with a Sennheiser MKH 50 from about 10 feet as the bird was sitting on a fence. The recording was made on a 100 meter pathway between the beach and a parking area.  The foliage on either side of the path is dense scrubby shrubs and trees.  On the opposite side of the path, but at the same point there was a White-eyed Vireo singing.  They are increasingly common on the coast of Georgia as they move through in early fall. In a poll of local birders one suggested an Empidonax flycatcher as the source, specifically Least Flycatcher. I think it is too fast for that species. I initially thought it might be a juvenile White-eyed Vireo because of the emphatic note at the end of the song, but the cadence is wrong for that species.

Location: Escanaba Township (near  Gladstone), Delta County, Michigan
Remarks:
I was walking in the woods, not too far from its edge on the meadow, when a pair of adult Ovenbirds became agitated and flew onto low branches of nearby trees, scolding me.  One circled around me and continued scolding. I believe I was very near their nest, so I left, watching the ground.  I did not see the nest.  These were alarm chip notes that I recorded.  Both birds' slight crests were raised.

Location: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
Remarks:
This file was originally posted as a mystery based on time of year for this location - extremely late, and location of the bird - the canopy of a tree.  I have since learned that this species will sing from a height of 5 to 8m, in spite of the fact it is a ground-nesting species. 
Two other factors convinced me the call is correct.  The spectral signature, while missing the first note, is very similar to one seen and recorded by another member of XC, and suggests this call is plastic, and perhaps still being learned. Finally, a friend with a very well respected ear, and years of field work with birds, heard one in early June in an adjacent county, identical to this recording.

Location: Division No. 4, Subd. A (near  La Poile), Division No. 4, Newfoundland and Labrador
Remarks:
This is an interesting recording from the Starlight Trail, in the Table Mountains of southwestern Newfoundland. The persistent chip calls and occasional bouts of song are being given by adult Ovenbirds, of which there were four present during the observation. I was sitting on the ground for a better vantage, and the action was happening in the adjacent undergrowth. The adults were displacing each other and chasing each other around. There was one fledgling present, which was remaining motionless and silent.
Remarkably, this appears to be the first recording of this species from the island of Newfoundland in the xeno-canto archive.

Remarks:

Location: Ohoopee Dunes Natural Area, Emanuel County, Georgia
Remarks:
Observers were following up on a disjunct breeding population of OVENBIRDS first discovered at this particular location several years previously by Malcolm Hodges of the Nature Conservancy. We detected at least 2 individuals on this date. It is possible -- even likely -- that there are more birds both on this protected tract of sandhill habitat as well as on private lands along the same unique geologic chain of sandhills on the Ohoopee River. There are other disjunct breeding sites for OVENBIRD in Georgia, including in Bibb County and in Burke County (on and just below the Fall Line, respectively). This site, however, is notably south of the Fall Line. At the moment, it appears to be the southern-most known breeding area for OVENBIRD in the world.

Natural sound. Bird foraging in the lower branches of a Tulip Poplar on the edge of the grounds, 3-6m above the ground. Mostly moving along the branches picking from the leaves. Occasionally sallying to catch an insect in the air. 
Habitat
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus
Editing
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz
Equipment
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

I have heard this bird many times this spring and last spring. I'm thinking it's a derivative song of some common species around here, perhaps a Tufted Titmouse, Hooded Warbler, or Yellow-throated Warbler.
There are 4 notes: wa wa WHEET WHEET! The last two are higher in pitch and louder.
The habitat is forest. It seems to be at 10 feet or higher elevations from ground. Have tired calling it in with Hooded and Yellow-throated Warbler songs (Birdjam). Did not appear to do anything.
Has anyone heard this song? Please help!
Signed,
Very Frustrated
UPDATE.  2 Jun 2013
After reading through the replies and listening to many more American redstart songs, I have found a song that matches what I am hearing.
http://m.youtube.com/#/watch?v=hvVywNI2n8A&desktop_uri=%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DhvVywNI2n8A
Thank you, guys, for your expert advice!

A short, bright warbler like song can be heard at 0:09. Sings just once on the cut. It was singing (unseen) from a medium sized tree at edge of the wide road cut, bordering second-growth humid broadleaf forest (overgrown 60-year mahogany and cacao plantation). The bird was with a small flock of migratory warblers (Setophaga ruticilla, Mniotilta varia for example). The tone seems to match recordings of Setophaga ruticilla, which was definitely present in the tree.  The pattern is not typical of this species, but there is much variation in pattern in this species.

Natural sound. Bird singing from midway up a large Southern Red Oak tree. 
Habitat
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus
Editing
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz
Equipment
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

This 20-second recording documents 3 songs of a Northern Parula. This bird was perched in a Black Cottonwood. This species is a very low density breeder in California. 
This recording was made with an iPhone 4s with a Sennheiser shotgun microphone and Røde Rec application. This recording has not been modified or edited.
Additional details and context may be found at: http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S23840906
Presumably this is the same singer initially located by Lauren and Gary Lester on 20150601 and subsequently refound by a few others. Today it was refound (41.300333, -124.044660) by song which was sung incessantly every 10-25 seconds during the entire duration of recordist was present. This bird was seen briefly in a tall black cottonwood. It spent most of the 35 minutes that I was there, too far from the road to see. Song audio recorded; will post to XC. Incidentally, Matt Lau photo-documented a silent second bird (41.301265, -124.047108) in his checklist (http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S23841735) about 200 meters to west of this bird. His sighting was contemporaneous with my sighting.

Location: Hiawatha National Forest (near  Rapid River), Delta County, Michigan
Type: life stage uncertain, sex uncertain, song
Remarks:
Windy (10-15 mph sustained) conditions resulting in leaf noise and creaking branches. This is an excerpt taken from a longer recording, when the bird sang while the wind was momentarily quiet . Another longer recording will be submitted of the same bird singing. Trees were close together,  mixed conifer and deciduous, and the bird was moving around at least 8 meters up in the trees. I could not see it. The ending of the song is a down then upward slur, which is like the birds in the western part of the range and was quite consistent (not the up/down chip of the more eastern birds). It is Type C of the Northern Parula songs described by Stephenson and Whittle on p. 370 of The Warbler Guide.

Hybrid Northern X Tropical Parula. Would not let me proceed without selecting one specific species so chose to enter as "Northern" Parula based on the fact that this species breeds in this location. 
Appears to be the same bird I photographed in September of 2013. Same general area as the bird I had previously observed. Male, singing on territory. 
Lacked dark necklace of Northern but with traces of darker coloration in same area. More extensive yellow, extending down the belly. Presence of incomplete, lower eye-arc (no upper eye-arc) and blotchy, well-defined orange coloration on the breast seem to suggest a hybrid Northern X Tropical Parula. 
Knocks against pure Tropical lineage are the presence of a lower eye-arc, lack of a smooth transition of yellow-orange coloration on the breast and belly (there's a well-defined blotch of orange that doesn't "fade" into the yellow), weak, black mask and darker coloration near the throat, which hints at a breast band. 
Several years ago, there was a record of TRPA from nearby Hamilton Pool. It is possible that this bird could be the offspring if that bird nested.

Location: Hiawatha National Forest (near  Rapid River), Delta County, Michigan
Type: life stage uncertain, sex uncertain, song
Remarks:
Windy (10-15 mph sustained) conditions resulting in leaf noise and creaking branches. This is a longer recording  with more songs than the excerpt that is XC660602. Trees were close together,  mixed conifer and deciduous, and the bird was moving around at least 8 meters up in the trees. I could not see it. There are about 28 phrases in the first section. The ending of the song is a down then upward slur, which is like the birds in the western part of the range and was quite consistent (not the up/down chip of the more eastern birds). It is Type C of the Northern Parula songs described by Stephenson and Whittle on p. 370 of The Warbler Guide.
